stimulus: Welcome to the experiment. Press any key to begin.

Instructions

In this experiment, you will see two Random Dot Kinematograms (RDKs) displayed simultaneously.

An RDK is a visual stimulus consisting of many small dots that move coherently in a single direction. In this experiment, the dots will be either white or black (see the short demo below for an example of an RDK stimulus).

On each trial, the two RDKs will move in different directions. Your task is to decide which RDK appears to contain more dots.

The RDK that you judge to have more dots is called the target RDK. For example, if the white RDK appears to have more dots than the black RDK, you should report the motion direction of the white RDK.

After viewing the RDKs, you will rotate a bar to indicate the perceived direction of the target RDK using the left and right arrow keys. Press Enter when you are satisfied with your response. When the bar is held down, the rotation speed increases.

You will receive points based on the accuracy of your response, and your final bonus reward may depend on your overall performance. Please try to respond as accurately as possible.

You will first complete 16 practice trials. Press the Enter key to start the practice phase.
